  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with severe penalties. The penalties for money laundering are outlined primarily in the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957) and other related statutes. Here are the key penalties:\n\n### 1. **Criminal Penalties**\n   - **Imprisonment**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in federal prison**. The length of the sentence depends on the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and the defendant's role in the scheme.\n   - **Fines**: The maximum fine for money laundering is **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater**.\n   - **Forfeiture**: Convicted individuals may also be required to forfeit the laundered funds and any property involved in or derived from the illegal activity.\n\n### 2. **Enhanced Penalties**\n   - If the money laundering activity involves proceeds from specified unlawful activities (SUAs) such as drug trafficking, terrorism, or serious violent crimes, the penalties can be more severe.\n   - In cases involving large sums of money or international transactions, additional charges or penalties may apply.\n\n### 3. **Civil Penalties**\n   - Individuals or entities may face **civil penalties** even without a criminal conviction. These can include fines of up to **$10,000 or the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater**.\n   - Financial institutions and businesses found to have violated anti-money laundering (AML) regulations may face additional civil penalties and sanctions.\n\n### 4. **Other Consequences**\n   - Convictions for money laundering can lead to **loss of professional licenses**, **ineligibility for government contracts**, and **damage to personal and business reputations**.\n   - Non-U.S. citizens convicted of money laundering may face **deportation or denial of entry** into the United States.\n\n### 5. **Aggravating Factors**\n   - Penalties may be enhanced if the money laundering activity involves:\n     - High-value transactions.\n     - Use of financial institutions to facilitate the crime.\n     - Involvement in organized crime or terrorism.\n     - Obstruction of justice or other criminal activities in connection with the laundering.\n\n### Key Statutes:\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits conducting or attempting to conduct financial transactions involving illicit proceeds with the intent to promote criminal activity, conceal the nature of the funds, or evade reporting requirements.\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits engaging in monetary transactions in criminally derived property exceeding $10,000.\n\nMoney laundering cases are prosecuted aggressively by federal agencies such as the **Department of Justice (DOJ)**, **Internal Revenue Service (IRS)**, and **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**. Legal representation is critical for anyone facing such charges.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
